What I don't like about this game is that it doesn't give you a lot of options. In GTA 4 you could decide who lives and make important plot decisions wihich gave it replay value, this gsme wasted a lot of opportunity to do that. The lock on controls can often lead to wasting ammo and targeting randoms when you're trying to shoot enemies, the controls for driving and breaking locks/sealing doors seem very rigid, but honestly I would recommend it nonetheless. The drug dealing adds a lotnof replay value, getting guns and new safehouses is very easy, the plot isn't bad for what it is, and while clunky the controls for breaking things like windows are pretty innovative. I'd say 4/5, cause that they should have implemented more that worked from previous games.

It was a great game on the DS and it translates well to the touch screen phone. The little mini-games for breaking into a car are gimmicky and probably should have been left out or adjusted for 2017. But otherwise it's a very cool game with a huge city to explore and great graphics that look as sharp as ever on a 1080p or higher screen (compared to the low resolution Nintendo DS screens).   Get yourself a cheap $10 bluetooth controller on Amazon and it makes it feel like you are playing on a PSP or Vita, lol. I was even able to cast the game to my TV and use my Bluetooth controller but there was a little lag. I think if I had used my screen instead of Bluetooth it might have played better as that was 3 things running wirelessly together.   I would love to see a sequel utilizing the same engine with maybe some tweaks here and there and a larger different city! Anyone complaining about this game never grew up playing GTA 1 and 2 on the PC or PS1 (top down was the hook up!).

This is an incredible game that packs a lot into such a small screen. The feel of GTA isn't lost - the dry satire carries in spite of the static cartoon cutscenes. Customisable controls is very handy (I moved the reverse/brake to be horiztonal next to accelerate, and put primary weapon vertically up, and chose manual steering). Auto aim is a bit janky but not so bad to hinder playing. I like the over the top weapons like chainsaw and mining making a comeback. And especially love the touch events (e.g. tapping repeatedly to smash windscreen when car goes into water, or arming a bomb) - I guess they were designed for DS but they work super well on Android. The trading part of the game is hugely addicting. Only problems / missing features imo are - would be great to have a google play cloud save for the save file and SD card support - it's a big app so these would both help a lot.

The GTA games are easily my favorite video game series.  Chinatown Wars is actually my favorite single-player experience of them all. It plays like an angled, isometric GTA 2, but takes place in the GTA IV rendering of Liberty City. Unlike III, Vice city, and San Andreas, CW was built for handheld systems. It played amazingly on my PSP, and the gameplay mechanics are easy to pick up and fun to use. And the soundtrack is of custom made songs (really catchy ones) specifically for the game itself.

A brilliant re-imagining of the older 2D GTA games with a huge explorable world and a ridiculously addictive contraband dealing minigame as its standouts. Unfortunately, the age of the game also shows through with some low-quality audio and art assets on show (though the game has largely been given a HD facelift), and sometimes needlessly frustrating missions absent mid-mission checkpoints, the latter often made even worse due to the game's borderline terrible touchscreen controls - though the game does provide support for controllers and has customization options that do try to mitigate this to some extent. Still, the game is a fantastically well made handheld classic, and if you can get put up with these problems you're in for a lot of fun.
